<body>
  <header>
    <div>
      <h1 style="margin:0; font-size:1.1rem;">Theme Toggle (Singleton Demo)</h1>
      <div class="muted">Demonstrates singleton-managed theme across elements</div>
    </div>
    <div class="controls">
      <button id="toggleBtn" aria-pressed="false">Toggle Theme</button>
      <button id="resetBtn">Reset to Light</button>
    </div>
  </header>

  <main>
    <section class="card">
      <h2>Card A</h2>
      <p class="muted">This card's style responds to theme changes.</p>
      <div>Status: <span class="status" id="statusA">light</span></div>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Card B</h2>
      <p class="muted">Another component reading the same theme singleton.</p>
      <div>Status: <span class="status" id="statusB">light</span></div>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Card C</h2>
      <p class="muted">Multiple elements sync through the same instance.</p>
      <div>Status: <span class="status" id="statusC">light</span></div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <script>
    /*
      ThemeManager implemented as a singleton.
      It exposes getInstance() which always returns the same object.
      The instance manages theme state, persists it to localStorage,
      and notifies subscribers when the theme changes.
    */
    const ThemeManager = (function () {
      // Private variables in module scope
      let instance = null;
      const STORAGE_KEY = 'demo_theme_singleton_v1';

      function createInstance() {
        // Private state
        let theme = readStoredTheme() || 'light';
        const subscribers = new Set();

        function readStoredTheme() {
          try {
            return localStorage.getItem(STORAGE_KEY);
          } catch (e) {
            return null;
          }
        }

        function persistTheme() {
          try {
            localStorage.setItem(STORAGE_KEY, theme);
          } catch (e) { /* ignore */ }
        }

        function applyToDocument() {
          // Apply a class to documentElement so CSS variables toggle
          if (theme === 'dark') {
            document.documentElement.classList.add('dark');
          } else {
            document.documentElement.classList.remove('dark');
          }
        }

        // initialise
        applyToDocument();

        return {
          getTheme() { return theme; },
          setTheme(newTheme) {
            if (newTheme !== 'light' && newTheme !== 'dark') return;
            if (theme === newTheme) return;
            theme = newTheme;
            persistTheme();
            applyToDocument();
            // notify
            subscribers.forEach(fn => {
              try { fn(theme); } catch (e) { /* ignore subscriber errors */ }
            });
          },
          toggle() {
            this.setTheme(theme === 'light' ? 'dark' : 'light');
          },
          subscribe(fn) {
            subscribers.add(fn);
            // return unsubscribe function
            return () => subscribers.delete(fn);
          }
        };
      }

      // Public API: always returns the same instance
      return {
        getInstance() {
          if (!instance) {
            instance = createInstance();
          }
          return instance;
        }
      };
    })();

    // ---- Usage demonstration ----
    const manager = ThemeManager.getInstance();

    // Elements that reflect the theme
    const statusA = document.getElementById('statusA');
    const statusB = document.getElementById('statusB');
    const statusC = document.getElementById('statusC');
    const toggleBtn = document.getElementById('toggleBtn');
    const resetBtn = document.getElementById('resetBtn');

    function updateUI(theme) {
      statusA.textContent = theme;
      statusB.textContent = theme;
      statusC.textContent = theme;
      toggleBtn.setAttribute('aria-pressed', theme === 'dark' ? 'true' : 'false');
      toggleBtn.textContent = theme === 'dark' ? 'Switch to Light' : 'Switch to Dark';
    }

    // Initial sync
    updateUI(manager.getTheme());

    // Subscribe so all components update when theme changes
    const unsubscribe = manager.subscribe(updateUI);

    // Buttons wired to the same singleton
    toggleBtn.addEventListener('click', () => manager.toggle());
    resetBtn.addEventListener('click', () => manager.setTheme('light'));

    // Example showing that multiple parts of the app calling getInstance() get the same shared object
    // (simulate another module grabbing the instance later)
    setTimeout(() => {
      const anotherRef = ThemeManager.getInstance();
      console.log('Same instance?', anotherRef === manager);
      // change theme through anotherRef to show global effect
      // anotherRef.setTheme('dark'); // uncomment to test
    }, 500);
  </script>
</body>
</html>

Why singletons are often terrible (short summary)
- Hidden global state: Singletons act like global variables. Their state can be accessed and mutated from anywhere, making reasoning about code flow and interactions harder.
- Tight coupling: Code that directly calls ThemeManager.getInstance() becomes coupled to that global implementation, making it hard to swap or vary behavior (e.g., for testing or in different environments).
- Difficult to test: Because the singleton hides its state across tests, tests can leak state to each other unless you explicitly reset it. Mocking or stubbing singletons often requires awkward hacks.
- Lifecycle uncertainty: It's not always clear when the singleton is initialized or reset. This can cause initialization order issues.
- Inflexibility: Singletons make it harder to support multiple instances if you later need them (for example, multiple independent themes or per-component scopes).
- Hidden dependencies: Functions and modules that use a singleton may not declare their dependency explicitly, reducing clarity and making dependency graphs harder to follow.

Better alternatives
- Dependency injection: Pass the needed object (theme manager, logger, store) into constructors or function parameters. This makes dependencies explicit and easy to substitute (for tests or different implementations).
- Module pattern with exported factory: Export a factory function that creates instances. Consumers can create instances as needed; tests can pass a test double.
- Context objects / provider patterns: In UI frameworks (React, Vue) use context/providers to give controlled access to shared state. That makes parts of the app explicit consumers of the context and simplifies testing.
- Event buses or observable stores: Use a small pub/sub or observable store which can be instantiated and injected where needed. That keeps state manageable and explicit.
- Immutable state / central stores: Use Redux-like stores or other predictable state containers where reads and writes follow clear rules; these are easier to test and reason about than hidden singletons.
- For simple cross-component UI needs: use local component state lifted up to a shared parent, or a framework's built-in state management, rather than a global singleton.

When a singleton can be acceptable
- Truly application-wide, unchanging services (configuration lookup, platform adapter) where only one concrete instance makes sense and the overhead of DI is unnecessary.
- As a lightweight convenience in small demos or prototypes. Still be mindful of the drawbacks and refactor as the codebase grows.

