I can do that. I’ll be direct: true JavaScript running in a single browser tab has a single-threaded event loop, so you won’t see classic memory-race behavior like in preemptive multithreading (simultaneous concurrent execution of two CPU threads touching the same memory). However, you can and do get real-world “race” problems that arise from asynchronous interleaving of operations — different tasks scheduled at different times reading, modifying, and writing shared state in a way that makes the final result depend on timing. Those are real concurrency bugs in the sense that they are timing-dependent and non-deterministic.

Below is a single self-contained HTML file that demonstrates such a timing-dependent bug. It shows two counter widgets side-by-side:

- The left widget ("Buggy") performs an asynchronous increment that reads the shared counter, then uses setTimeout to simulate async work, then writes the incremented value back. Rapid repeated clicks schedule overlapping async operations; because each callback uses a stale read of the shared value, increments can be lost.
- The right widget ("Fixed") performs the same user-visible workflow but uses an update function that computes the new value from the current shared state at the moment of application (atomic update pattern). This prevents lost updates even under overlapping async operations.

