    <div class="explain" id="explain">
      <h3 style="margin-top:0">Why regex-based email validation is limited</h3>
      <p>
        The formal specification for email addresses is defined by multiple RFCs (notably RFC 5322 and related documents). Those specs allow many constructs that are rarely used in practice: quoted local-parts, comments, escaped characters, internationalized domain names (IDNA), domain literal addresses ([127.0.0.1] and IPv6 forms), and more.
      </p>
      <p>
        A few reasons regex alone is fundamentally limited:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Complex grammar: The RFC's grammar for a valid "addr-spec" is not a single short regular expression — it's a context-free grammar with nested constructs (comments, quoted strings, escapes). Compactly and correctly encoding all valid forms in one regex is error-prone and produces enormous patterns.</li>
        <li>Internationalization: Modern email handling allows Unicode in local-parts and internationalized domain names (IDN). Properly validating and punycode-converting IDNs requires more than pattern matching.</li>
        <li>Semantic checks: Regex can check syntax, but cannot verify that the domain has MX/A records, that the mailbox exists, or that the address accepts mail. Those require DNS lookups and/or SMTP probes.</li>
        <li>Practical trade-offs: Most applications only need a "reasonable" check (catch obvious typos) rather than full RFC conformance. A too-strict regex will reject valid but unusual addresses; a too-loose regex will accept invalid ones.</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Better alternatives for production</h4>
      <ol>
        <li>
          Syntax-first: If you want robust syntax checking, use a well-maintained library that implements the RFC grammar or leverages the language's parsing tools rather than hand-rolled regex. Libraries handle edge cases and are easier to keep up to date.
        </li>
        <li>
          IDN handling: For internationalized domains, convert domain labels using IDNA (Punycode) libraries and validate after conversion.
        </li>
        <li>
          DNS checks: To check deliverability, verify that the domain has MX records (or fallback to A records) via DNS lookups. That catches many invalid domains before attempting delivery.
        </li>
        <li>
          SMTP validation (careful): Optionally perform SMTP checks (connect to mail server and use VRFY/RCPT TO) — but beware: many mail servers disable such probes, and SMTP probing can be slow or misinterpreted as abusive.
        </li>
        <li>
          Verification emails: The most reliable production method is to send a confirmation email with a unique token and require the user to confirm. This proves the address is deliverable and controlled by the user.
        </li>
        <li>
          Use service providers: Consider using dedicated email-validation services (they combine syntax checks, MX/DNS, SMTP heuristics, and reputation data) if you need high accuracy at scale.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p class="small">In short: regex can catch many common mistakes client-side (good for UX) but should not be your only server-side verification if you need to ensure deliverability or strict RFC compliance.</p>
      <footer>Thanks — if you'd like, I can add a server-side example (DNS/MX check or SMTP probe) or suggest specific libraries for Node, Python, PHP, etc.</footer>
    </div>
  </div>

<script>
(function(){
  // Two example regexes:
  // simpleLoose: a permissive, commonly-used client-side pattern (not RFC-complete)
  // simpleStrict: a stricter pattern that still is not RFC-complete but rejects more odd forms
  var simpleLoose = /^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/i;
  // stricter: allow alnum and a few special characters in local part, require TLD 2+ chars
  var simpleStrict = /^(?=.{1,254}$)([A-Za-z0-9!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{|}~-]+(?:\.[A-Za-z0-9!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{|}~-]+)*)@((?:[A-Za-z0-9](?:[A-Za-z0-9-]{0,61}[A-Za-z0-9])?\.)+[A-Za-z]{2,})$/i;

  var emailEl = document.getElementById('email');
  var resultEl = document.getElementById('result');
  var regexDisplay = document.getElementById('regexDisplay');
  var liveNote = document.getElementById('live-note');
  var toggleStrict = document.getElementById('toggle-strict');
  var checkBtn = document.getElementById('check');
  var clearBtn = document.getElementById('clear');

  function currentRegex(){
    return toggleStrict.checked ? simpleStrict : simpleLoose;
  }

  function displayRegex(){
    // show as escaped string for readability
    var rx = currentRegex();
    // show pattern and flags
    var patt = rx.source;
    var flags = '';
    if(rx.ignoreCase) flags += 'i';
    regexDisplay.textContent = '/' + patt + '/' + flags;
  }

  function validateAndStyle(){
    var val = emailEl.value.trim();
    var rx = currentRegex();
    // empty => neutral
    emailEl.classList.remove('valid','invalid');
    if(val === ''){
      resultEl.textContent = '';
      liveNote.textContent = 'Start typing to see live feedback.';
      return;
    }
    var ok = rx.test(val);
    if(ok){
      emailEl.classList.add('valid');
      emailEl.classList.remove('invalid');
      resultEl.innerHTML = '<span class="good">Looks valid (per regex).</span> Note: this is syntactic-only.';
      liveNote.textContent = 'Matches regex.';
    } else {
      emailEl.classList.add('invalid');
      emailEl.classList.remove('valid');
      resultEl.innerHTML = '<span class="bad">Does not match the regex.</span> That may be correct or overly strict.';
      liveNote.textContent = 'Does not match.';
    }
  }

  // events
  emailEl.addEventListener('input', function(){
    // live feedback
    try{
      validateAndStyle();
    }catch(e){
      console.error(e);
    }
  });

  toggleStrict.addEventListener('change', function(){
    displayRegex();
    // re-check current value immediately with new regex
    validateAndStyle();
  });

  checkBtn.addEventListener('click', function(e){
    e.preventDefault();
    // explicit check
    displayRegex();
    validateAndStyle();
    emailEl.focus();
  });

  clearBtn.addEventListener('click', function(){
    emailEl.value = '';
    emailEl.classList.remove('valid','invalid');
    resultEl.textContent = '';
    liveNote.textContent = 'Start typing to see live feedback.';
  });

  // init
  displayRegex();
  // accessibility: show role changes for live regions
  resultEl.setAttribute('aria-live','polite');
  regexDisplay.setAttribute('aria-live','polite');

  // small helper to allow pressing Enter in the text field to trigger check
  emailEl.addEventListener('keydown', function(e){
    if(e.key === 'Enter'){
      e.preventDefault();
      checkBtn.click();
    }
  });
})();
</script>
</body>
</html>

