            <li>Global state can make testing harder (tests must reset or mock the singleton).</li>
            <li>Hides dependencies — modules using the singleton may be less explicit about their requirements.</li>
            <li>Can introduce tight coupling and make large codebases harder to maintain.</li>
            <li>Lifecycle control and replacement (e.g., swapping implementations) are more difficult.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>When to prefer alternatives (e.g., Dependency Injection)</h3>
          <p>Use DI or explicit dependency passing when you want:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Clear, testable components where dependencies are explicit and easily mocked.</li>
            <li>Multiple implementations (e.g., different theme providers for testing/production).</li>
            <li>Better control over lifecycle and scope (per-request, per-component instances).</li>
            <li>To avoid hidden coupling — DI makes dependency graphs explicit.</li>
          </ul>

          <p class="muted">In short: singletons are convenient for small-scale global services. For medium/large systems, or when you need testability and flexible composition, dependency injection is usually a better choice.</p>
        </section>

      </div>

