<h3>Stack-overflow risks, practical solutions, and explanation</h3>
<ul>
<li>Stack-overflow risk: each recursive call consumes a stack frame. Deep recursion can exhaust the language runtime's call stack and throw an error (in browsers this is typically a RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded).</li>
<li>Practical solutions demonstrated in this page:
  <ul>
    <li>Convert recursion to iteration using an explicit stack (LIFO data structure). This avoids using the language call stack and prevents stack overflow for the same logical depth.</li>
    <li>Use smaller recursion depth (limit problem size) or redesign algorithm to be tail-recursive where supported. JavaScript engines do not reliably implement tail-call elimination, so tail recursion is not a dependable solution in browsers.</li>
    <li>Use trampolining (break recursive work into repeated loop steps) to avoid deep call chains; this effectively converts recursion to iteration at the application level.</li>
    <li>Use continuation-passing or asynchronous chunking (setTimeout / requestAnimationFrame) to split work into smaller call chains to avoid long blocking stacks and keep UI responsive.</li>
  </ul>
</li>
<li>Trade-offs: iterative solutions require manual stack/state management but are robust. Tail-call elimination is ideal but not portable in JS. Chunking helps responsiveness but adds complexity.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Concise proof of understanding of recursion</h4>
<p>
Recursion defines a function in terms of itself and requires:
(1) a base case that terminates recursion, and
(2) a rule that reduces the problem toward the base case.
By induction: if the function is correct for n=1 (base) and if correctness at n-1 implies correctness at n via the recursive step, the function is correct for all finite n. Practically, each recursive call uses a stack frame storing local variables and the return address; unbounded recursion can exhaust available stack memory.
</p>

