Explanation (brief):
- The bug happens because operations are not atomic. Each task does: read sharedCounter, compute new value, then write it back. If two tasks read the same old value before either writes, one of their increments is overwritten — lost update.
- Fix approaches demonstrated:
  - Actor (serialized queue): all increment requests are queued and applied one at a time by a single async loop. No two tasks can update concurrently.
  - Mutex (Promise lock): a lightweight promise-based lock chains update operations so only one runs the critical section at a time.

You can change number of tasks, units per task, and the async delay to make the bug more or less likely. The page logs each task's observation and final totals so you can see exactly how updates were lost and how the fixes avoid that.

I can help with that — I’ll provide a single self-contained HTML file that demonstrates (1) a leaking implementation that accumulates memory by retaining event listeners and DOM references when widgets are removed, and (2) a fixed implementation that properly cleans up. I’ll also include a simple widget-count tracker to show how many active widgets the app thinks it has and explain why blaming the garbage collector is usually wrong in these cases.

Notes before the code
- The “leak” shown is created by keeping references to DOM elements and event callbacks after widgets are removed. That prevents JavaScript’s garbage collector (GC) from reclaiming those objects, so the memory use grows. The GC itself is not “broken” — the program is retaining references.
- Typical causes of leaks: closures holding references, custom event listeners that are not removed, global arrays/Maps/Sets that retain objects, timers not cleared, and circular references combined with external (non-JS) references (rare in modern engines).
- The fixed version removes event listeners, clears timers, and drops stored references so the GC can reclaim memory.

