});

document.getElementById('showExplanationBtn').addEventListener('click', () => {
  document.getElementById('explainArea').innerHTML = [
    'Why floating point fails for money (short explanation):',
    '',
    '- JavaScript Number is a binary floating-point (IEEE-754 double). Many decimal fractions',
    '  like 0.1 or 4.99 have no exact representation in binary, so they are stored as',
    '  nearby binary fractions.',
    '- Arithmetic on these approximations produces small rounding errors. For example,',
    '  0.1 + 0.2 is stored as 0.30000000000000004, not exactly 0.3.',
    '- Using === compares the raw binary values. Two results that look the same when',
    '  printed with two decimals can still differ internally (so === can be false).',
    '- For money you typically need exact decimal arithmetic. Common practical options:',
    '  * Store amounts as integer cents (e.g., 4.99 -> 499) and do integer arithmetic.',
    '  * Use a decimal arithmetic library (decimal.js, Big.js, Dinero.js) that models',
    '    decimal fractions exactly.',
    '  * Use BigInt to store cents if you prefer arbitrary large integers.',
    '',
    'In short: Do not use raw floating point for financial equality/tests or totals; use',
    'an integer cents representation or a decimal library.',
  ].join('\\n');
});

